SR Verification Input Files
===========================

Testbench: 128-unit chain (512 thermometer bits total)
Reset code: 256 (units 0-63 ON, units 64-127 OFF)
Reset signal: vin_rst_b[0:63] = 0, vin_rst_b[64:127] = 1
Reset vsel: 3 (decimal) = 11 (binary)

Monitored Units
---------------
4 units at the ON/OFF boundary after reset:

  Unit 62: ON  (code 4, vout = 1111) — 2nd-to-last fully ON unit
  Unit 63: ON  (code 4, vout = 1111) — last fully ON unit (boundary)
  Unit 64: OFF (code 0, vout = 0000) — first fully OFF unit (boundary)
  Unit 65: OFF (code 0, vout = 0000) — 2nd fully OFF unit

  Why these 4: All shifting action happens at the ON/OFF boundary.
  Units 62-63 have output=1 and units 64-65 have output=0 after reset.
  As the code increases (CW), ones fill from unit 63 into unit 64, then 65.
  As the code decreases (CCW), ones retract from unit 64 back into unit 63, then 62.
  These 4 units capture all boundary transitions and direction reversals.

Files
-----
vsel_stimulus.txt
  - 78 lines, one value per line
  - Each value is the decimal encoding of vsel<1:0>:
      0 = vsel<1:0> = 00
      1 = vsel<1:0> = 01
      2 = vsel<1:0> = 10
      3 = vsel<1:0> = 11
  - Line 1 is the initial state after reset (vsel=3)
  - Lines 2-78 are successive gray code steps (CW or CCW)
  - Gray code CW (UP):  3 → 1 → 0 → 2 → 3 → ...
  - Gray code CCW (DN): 3 → 2 → 0 → 1 → 3 → ...

expected_outputs.txt / expected_stress.txt
  - One integer per line = decimal value of the 16 monitored output bits
  - The 16 bits [u62_vout0 ... u65_vout3] are treated as a binary word:
      MSB = u62_vout0, LSB = u65_vout3
  - Range: 0 to 65535 (2^16 - 1)
  - After reset: u62=1111, u63=1111, u64=0000, u65=0000 → 65280 (0xFF00)
  - Each CW step adds one bit from the right: 65280 → 65408 → 65472 → ...
  - Each CCW step removes one bit from the right: 65280 → 61440 → ...
  - Line N corresponds to the expected decimal value after applying vsel line N

Test Sequence Summary (vsel_stimulus.txt / expected_outputs.txt)
----------------------------------------------------------------
Line 1:      Initial state after reset (code 256)
Lines 2-9:   CW x8 (code 256 → 264) — fills into unit 64
Lines 10-13: CCW x4 (264 → 260) — immediate direction reversal
Lines 14-25: CCW x12 (260 → 248) — crosses back into unit 62
Lines 26-27: CW x2 (248 → 250) — reversal after long CCW sweep
Lines 28-37: CW x10 (250 → 260) — sweep back through boundary
Lines 38-45: CCW/CW alternating x4 (jitter test at boundary)
Lines 46-53: CW x8 (260 → 268) — push into unit 65
Lines 54-73: CCW x20 (268 → 248) — long sweep back
Line 74:     CW x1 (248 → 249) — reversal after long sweep
Line 75:     CCW x1 (249 → 248) — immediate re-reversal
Lines 76-78: CW x3 (248 → 251) — final steps

Usage
-----
In OCEAN/Spectre: read vsel_stimulus.txt line-by-line, apply each value
to vsel<1:0>, wait for settling, then compare vout of monitored units
against the corresponding line in expected_outputs.txt.

Threshold for digital comparison: VDD/2 = 0.45V


Stress Test Files
=================

vsel_stress.txt / expected_stress.txt
  - 121 lines each, same format as above
  - Targets edge cases NOT covered by the main stimulus:

  Test 1 (lines 2-21): Boundary oscillation at code 256/257
    Rapid CW/CCW toggling at the exact inter-unit boundary (unit 63→64).
    Exercises: pair capture/release at the most fragile point, inter-unit
    wire switching every cycle.

  Test 2 (lines 22-31): Reversal from every vsel state
    Steps CW to reach vsel=1, reverses; then to vsel=0, reverses; etc.
    Exercises: direction change from each of the 4 gray code states.
    Catches bugs where reversal from a specific vsel value fails.

  Test 3 (lines 32-65): Multi-unit cross + snap back
    CW 17 steps (crosses 4+ unit boundaries) then CCW 17 steps back.
    Exercises: long propagation chain settling, cumulative boundary effects.

  Test 4 (lines 66-73): Full intra-unit pair sweep
    Unit 64: code 0→1→2→3→4→3→2→1→0 (all 4 pair formations + releases).
    Exercises: every pair position within a single unit.

  Test 5 (lines 74-85): Reversal at each intra-unit code
    Steps to code 1, reverses; to code 2, reverses; to code 3, reverses;
    to code 4, reverses. Exercises: pair stability at each intermediate code.

  Test 6 (lines 86-94): Double/triple reversal patterns
    CW, CCW, CCW, CW, CW, CCW, CCW, CCW, CW.
    Exercises: multiple consecutive reversals, "zig-zag" behavior.

  Test 7 (lines 95-121): Boundary oscillation at unit 62/63 (code 252)
    Same as Test 1 but at the OTHER monitored boundary (going DOWN).
    Exercises: boundary oscillation in CCW direction.
